    </script><meta content="LearningHindi" property="fb:admins" /><meta content="Learning Hindi!" property="og:site_name" /><meta content="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/862964443/lesson-17-how-are-you" property="og:url" /><meta content="article" property="og:type" /><meta content="What are the first things you&rsquo;re going to want to say (in Hindi!) when you meet someone? Well, we&rsquo;ve already covered how to say Hello - we saw it in Intro #1. Can you remember what it is? That&rsquo;s right, we say &#2344;&#2350;&#2360;&#2381;&#2340;&#2375; namaste! So after you&rsquo;ve said that, what are you going to say next? How about maybe &lsquo;How are you?&rsquo;. That&rsquo;s what we&rsquo;re going to cover today!









 Whenever you meet someone try and practice your Hindi, even if it&rsquo;s just saying something simple like Hello, How are you?






 So let&rsquo;s get straight into it! Are you ready? To ask 'How are you?&rsquo; to a Male we say&hellip;







&#2310;&#2346; &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2375; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;? aap kaise hain? &nbsp; - How are you? (To a Male)


 Do you recognise any of the words we have used here? The first word here is &#2310;&#2346; aap - this is the polite and formal way to say You, as you may have seen in&nbsp;Lesson #15. Next we have the word &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2375; kaise&nbsp;this means 'like what&rsquo; or 'how&rsquo;. Finally,&nbsp;&#2361;&#2376;&#2306; hain - this means 'are&rsquo;. If you want you can learn more about &#2361;&#2376;&#2306; hain in Lesson #22.&nbsp;


 Whew! Ok, deep breath have you got it? We say &#2310;&#2346; &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2375; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;? aap kaise hain - How are you? (To a Male). When asking a &nbsp;female what we say is very slightly different, we say&hellip;










&#2310;&#2346; &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2368; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;? aap kaisee hain? &nbsp; - How are you? (To a Female)


 Can you see the difference? It&rsquo;s very small! &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2375; kaise has changed to &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2368;&nbsp;kaisee. It still means 'like what&rsquo; or 'how&rsquo;, but now it agrees with the feminine subject. Don&rsquo;t worry about this for now though, you&rsquo;ll be learning plenty more about it soon!





 So now you&rsquo;ve asked, 'How are you?&rsquo; you&rsquo;re going to want to be able to reply! Today we&rsquo;re just going to learn how to say 'I am ok&rsquo; and 'I am good&rsquo;, but if you want to learn some more replies then please check out Lesson #90.&nbsp;


 Saying 'I am ok&rsquo; is super easy! We just say&hellip;







&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2336;&#2368;&#2325; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305; main theek hoon - I am ok (Male and Female)


 The word &#2336;&#2368;&#2325;&nbsp;theek means 'ok&rsquo; and it&rsquo;s a very, very common Hindi word! You&rsquo;ll be hearing it all the time, so it&rsquo;s a good idea to learn it! Told you it was easy! Now to say 'I am good&rsquo; we say&hellip;










&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305; main acchaa hoon -&nbsp;I am good (Said by a Male)





&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2368; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305; main acchee hoon &nbsp;  -I am good (Said by a Female)


 Can you see the slight difference between them? I&rsquo;ve been using the word &#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366; acchaa&nbsp;quite a lot so you should be a little familiar with it by now, it just means 'good&rsquo;, or even 'great&rsquo;.&nbsp;


 And that&rsquo;s it for today! Try and practice over what you have learnt to help you remember it. Why not practice by asking your friends 'How are you?&rsquo; in Hindi and then teaching them the correct reply!&nbsp;


 Be sure to check out Lesson #90 to learn a few more exciting replies to this question!


