        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-17-how-are-you">Lesson #17: How Are You?</a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>What are the first things you&rsquo;re going to want to say (in Hindi!) when you meet someone? Well, we&rsquo;ve already covered how to say Hello - we saw it in <a href="http://t.umblr.com/redirect?z=http%3A%2F%2Flearning-hindi.com%2Fpost%2F716551335%2Flesson-1-hello&amp;t=OTRkNGYwNTI2MzIzZDhkNTY4MmE2ZDdmNWE4NWYzZjM2NzM1MDc4OSxIekhmWlBidA%3D%3D&amp;b=t%3Ahf3yIetu6VvjxJqY6DH92g&amp;p=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.learning-hindi.com%2Fpost%2F862964443%2Flesson-17-how-are-you&amp;m=0">Intro #1</a>. Can you remember what it is? That&rsquo;s right, we say <big><big>&#2344;&#2350;&#2360;&#2381;&#2340;&#2375;</big></big> <em>namaste</em>! So after you&rsquo;ve said that, what are you going to say next? How about maybe &lsquo;How are you?&rsquo;. That&rsquo;s what we&rsquo;re going to cover today!</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/b9e4be5407e797eb619523e1c22808e7/tumblr_inline_mnxj92VuD21qz4rgp.png"></p><blockquote><div><p>Whenever you meet someone try and practice your Hindi, even if it&rsquo;s just saying something simple like Hello, How are you?</p></div></blockquote><p>So let&rsquo;s get straight into it! Are you ready? To ask 'How are you?&rsquo; to a Male we say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F95561769&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2310;&#2346; &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2375; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;?</big></big> <em>aap kaise hain? &nbsp;<br>- </em>How are you? (To a Male)</p><p>Do you recognise any of the words we have used here? The first word here is <big><big>&#2310;&#2346;</big></big> <em>aap</em> - this is the polite and formal way to say You, as you may have seen in&nbsp;<a href="../853847321/lesson-15-pronouns">Lesson #15</a>. Next we have the word <big><big>&#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2375;</big></big> <em>kaise</em>&nbsp;this means 'like what&rsquo; or 'how&rsquo;. Finally,&nbsp;<big><big>&#2361;&#2376;&#2306;</big></big> <em>hain</em> - this means 'are&rsquo;. If you want you can learn more about <big><big>&#2361;&#2376;&#2306;</big></big> <em>hain</em> in <a href="../899032290/lesson-22-to-be">Lesson #22</a>.&nbsp;</p><p>Whew! Ok, deep breath have you got it? We say <big><big>&#2310;&#2346; &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2375; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;?</big></big> <em>aap kaise hain</em> - How are you? (To a Male). When asking a &nbsp;female what we say is very slightly different, we say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/610874f62911b9222f2d8180ddf00b6b/tumblr_inline_mnha0pX2Mu1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F95562312&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2310;&#2346; &#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2368; &#2361;&#2376;&#2306;?</big></big> <em>aap kaisee hain? &nbsp;<br>- </em>How are you? (To a Female)</p><p>Can you see the difference? It&rsquo;s very small! <big><big>&#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2375;</big></big> <em>kaise</em> has changed to <big><big>&#2325;&#2376;&#2360;&#2368;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>kaisee. </em>It still means 'like what&rsquo; or 'how&rsquo;, but now it agrees with the feminine subject. Don&rsquo;t worry about this for now though, you&rsquo;ll be learning plenty more about it soon!</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/10d95addccf3217a566e1791809bddc9/tumblr_inline_mnha1mYpPf1qz4rgp.png"></p><p>So now you&rsquo;ve asked, 'How are you?&rsquo; you&rsquo;re going to want to be able to reply! Today we&rsquo;re just going to learn how to say 'I am ok&rsquo; and 'I am good&rsquo;, but if you want to learn some more replies then please check out <a href="../3012228169/lesson-90-how-are-you-part-2-more-replies">Lesson #90</a>.&nbsp;</p><p>Saying 'I am ok&rsquo; is super easy! We just say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F95562623&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2336;&#2368;&#2325; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305;</big></big> <em>main theek hoon <br>-</em> I am ok (Male and Female)</p><p>The word <big><big>&#2336;&#2368;&#2325;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>theek</em> means 'ok&rsquo; and it&rsquo;s a very, very common Hindi word! You&rsquo;ll be hearing it all the time, so it&rsquo;s a good idea to learn it! Told you it was easy! Now to say 'I am good&rsquo; we say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/d2449c85325f52a9a9388e138651f7a8/tumblr_inline_mnha27Meqk1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F95562480&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305;</big></big> <em>main acchaa hoon <br>-&nbsp;</em>I am good (Said by a Male)</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/cbfead88e9fdddf5a17c810c8ab1b0b6/tumblr_inline_mnha2ju5yC1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2368; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305;</big></big> <em>main acchee hoon &nbsp;</em><br> -I am good (Said by a Female)</p><p>Can you see the slight difference between them? I&rsquo;ve been using the word <big><big>&#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366;</big></big> <em>acchaa</em>&nbsp;quite a lot so you should be a little familiar with it by now, it just means 'good&rsquo;, or even 'great&rsquo;.&nbsp;</p><p>And that&rsquo;s it for today! Try and practice over what you have learnt to help you remember it. Why not practice by asking your friends 'How are you?&rsquo; in Hindi and then teaching them the correct reply!&nbsp;</p><p>Be sure to check out <a href="../3012228169/lesson-90-how-are-you-part-2-more-replies">Lesson #90</a> to learn a few more exciting replies to this question!</p><p><a href="http://t.umblr.com/redirect?z=http%3A%2F%2Flearning-hindi.com%2Fconvo&amp;t=NjU4YTY4OTg2MjMwZmEwOGZhNTU4NzZjMWI5YzUyMWViZWJmMmZkMixIekhmWlBidA%3D%3D&amp;b=t%3Ahf3yIetu6VvjxJqY6DH92g&amp;p=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.learning-hindi.com%2Fpost%2F862964443%2Flesson-17-how-are-you&amp;m=0">Back to Conversational Hindi</a></p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/how-are-you">how are you</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/conversational">conversational</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/july2010">july2010</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="862964443" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_862964443"><iframe id="like_iframe_862964443" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=862964443&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=HzHfZPbt" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true"